  "text": "Furthermore, due to the very nature of P3, the less frequent a target is, the more of an ''oddball'' it becomes [CITATION_1] . Thus, P3 size is likely to be strongly modulated by frequency/oddball effects, which may not be related to the difficulty of identifying the stimulus, or to the amount of resources allocated to it. With this point in mind, the finding of less frequent targets eliciting a larger P3 (Figure 4 in [CITATION_2] does not per se provide evidence for the P3 component as a measure of resource allocation and does not contradict our results from Experiment 1.",
